<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011894-0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 005059 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
January 18, 1994, Tuesday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 1; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
92 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hick; Thuan Le, GOREN, ER,; Jeffrey A. Perlman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 TV TOWN HALL: Old-fashioned Town Hall meetings helped send Bill Clinton to the 
White House.Now he uses satellite "town halls" to stay in touch and sell his 
programs. One of them -- on arts and education -- takes place across the 
country today at 5:15 p.m. . . . To watch locally, you can show up at the 
county Board of Education office in Costa Mesa. Clinton's Education Secretary 
Richard Riley will talk by satellite with local leaders in arts and the schools 
about how the President intends to make the arts a part of his education 
reform. 
</P>
